Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
Yesterday, our Judiciary Committee passed HR 38, National Reciprocity. I support this bill, but there is a better option, and it is National Constitutional Carry.

29 states already have Constitutional (i.e. permitless) Carry. Why not extend it to all 50 states?

Under HR 38 (Reciprocity), a resident of one of the Constitutional Carry states can carry in any state that allows their citizens to obtain a permit. The recent ‚ÄúBruen‚Äù Supreme Court decision requires all states that aren‚Äôt Constitutional Carry to issue carry permits to their citizens.

This means that when HR 38 passes, any resident of those 29 Constitutional Carry states will be able to carry in any of the 50 states without a permit. Ironically, however, residents of the 21 states (like New York or California) that aren‚Äôt Constitutional Carry will need a permit to carry in their own state, while visitors from states that are Constitutional Carry (like Kentucky or Ohio) won‚Äôt need a permit to carry in states like New York or California.

If Congress, relying on the Second Amendment, can force California to allow ‚ÄúPermitless‚Äù Carry for Kentuckians who visit California, why would we not force California to allow ‚ÄúPermitless‚Äù Carry for Californians who are in California? In other words, why not pass National Constitutional Carry and afford everyone in the United States the right to ‚Äúbear arms‚Äù which is enshrined in the Constitution?

The other quirk of HR 38 is that (I believe) it would allow a person from Kentucky to carry an AR-15 pistol with a 20-round magazine in California, while Californians would not be allowed to carry, or even own, the same equipment. The Supreme Court decision in ‚ÄúD.C. v. Heller,‚Äù whether you agree with it or not, allows states to have some regulations on firearm equipment and eligibility to possess, but HR 38 seems to contradict that framework.

Contrast this with my National Constitutional Carry bill which basically says if a state allows people to possess (KEEP) a particular firearm, that state must also allow people to carry (BEAR) that firearm.

I introduced my National Constitutional Carry bill in committee yesterday as a substitute amendment to HR 38, National Reciprocity. After introducing the amendment for the record and describing it, I withdrew the amendment instead of putting my Judiciary Committee colleagues in the position of deciding whether to replace National Reciprocity with National Constitutional Carry. The dilemma is that not enough Republicans in the whole House understand the difference, and the prevailing opinion is that Reciprocity can pass the whole House, but Constitutional Carry cannot.

Perhaps when more of my colleagues who are not on the Judiciary Committee understand why we should pass National Constitutional Carry instead of (or in addition to) National Reciprocity, we can make a strong push to report National Constitutional Carry out of the Judiciary Committee for a vote in the full House of Representatives. In the meantime, I‚Äôm glad HR 38 is going to the House floor for a vote.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
The Trump administration‚Äôs escalating actions against free speech reflect a disturbing erosion of civil liberties. The surveillance, detention, and disappearance of Rumesya Ozturk ‚Äì taken off the street in Somerville by non-uniformed federal agents in an unmarked SUV ‚Äì raise serious concerns about constitutional rights and the unchecked use of government power.

ICE must immediately provide an update on her whereabouts, the justification for her detention, and the legal authority under which this was carried out.

Ms. Ozturk‚Äôs case appears to be the latest in an alarming crackdown on individuals who, despite being legally present in the United States, have been targeted for expressing views that the administration opposes. Why are students, journalists, and activists being subjected to surveillance, visa revocations, and even threats of deportation without due process?

This is a direct attack on the foundation of our democracy, and it sets a dangerous precedent. If this administration can silence lawful dissent today, what stops them from silencing American citizens tomorrow? The United States has long condemned authoritarian regimes for abducting dissidents ‚Äì yet now, our own government is using the same tactics.

The American people deserve answers, accountability, and a government that defends their freedoms, not one that tramples on them.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
I‚Äôve spent the past few days reflecting on the incredible life Kitty Dukakis. I‚Äôm heartbroken by the loss of such a remarkable woman whose kindness, strength and unwavering spirit touched so many lives ‚Äì including mine. Since seeking public office, I was fortunate to spend time with Kitty and Governor Dukakis, often in the warmth of their home, where they welcomed me with the same generosity and grace they extended to so many.

Kitty and Mike shared a love that was deep, genuine, and enduring‚Äîa love that, even on her last day, was as strong as it was when they married 62 years ago. Their partnership was one of true devotion, rooted in an unshakable commitment to each other and to the values they held dear. Watching them together was a reminder of what it means to stand by someone in every joy and every challenge.

My heart is with Governor Dukakis and their entire family as they mourn this tremendous loss.

BREAKING: Rep. Miller Introduces the Keep Our Girls Safe Act Codifying President Trump‚Äôs Protections of Female Spaces

WASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äî Today, Congresswoman Mary Miller (IL-15) introduced the Keep Our Girls Safe Act, legislation that fully codifies President Trump‚Äôs Executive Order, Keeping Men Out of Women‚Äôs Sports, and ensures that public schools comply with federal mandates to protect female-only spaces or lose federal funding.

Rep. Miller‚Äôs bill directs the federal government to rescind federal funding to any public school in the United States that deprives women and girls of female-only spaces.

‚ÄúPresident Trump is boldly standing up for the safety and privacy of our daughters, now Congress must do the same,‚Äù said Congresswoman Mary Miller. ‚ÄúFemale-only spaces exist for a reason, and no girl should ever be put in an unsafe or uncomfortable situation. My bill ensures public schools follow the law‚Äîor lose federal funding.‚Äù

Great meeting with PA-1 community members Dr. Pamela Goldman of Yardley, along with osteopathic medical students Danielle Lapierre of Levittown and Surali Panchani of North Wales‚Äîdedicated members of the @AOAforDOs‚Äîfor a timely discussion on the challenges facing our healthcare system today.
 
We focused on two major priorities: the shortage of healthcare professionals and the need to expand access to telehealth. These issues go hand in hand, and addressing them is essential to strengthening care in our community and nationwide.
 
That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm advancing bipartisan solutions like the Telehealth Expansion Act, which would give over 32 million Americans with high-deductible plans access to virtual care, and the Medicare Patient Access and Practice Stabilization Act of 2025, to give providers the stability they need to continue serving patients effectively.
 
I‚Äôm grateful to Dr. Goldman, Danielle, and Surali for their insights and the work they're doing in our community. I look forward to carrying their perspectives with me as I continue working to ensure healthcare professionals have the resources and support they need to provide high-quality care to every American.

¬†
In the months since, we‚Äôve seen incredible progress‚Äîover 7.6 million cubic yards of debris removed, 1,332 roads reopened, and 272 bridges repaired or replaced. ¬†
This week, I met again with local leaders from WNC about the recovery progress, and one thing is clear: WNC needs more resources and less red tape to fully rebuild.

I will continue working with President Trump and his administration to make WNC whole again.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First 

Jennifer Freeman has lived in Kinston for the past 13 years. She is a U.S. Army veteran who served four years as a medic and a leave and finance clerk. After serving in the U.S. Army, she became a work-study student with the Kinston Veterans Service Center.

After completing her work-study, Jennifer served the North Carolina Department of Military and Veterans Affairs (NCDMVA) as a Veterans Technician Officer and later as a Veterans Service Officer (VSO).

Jennifer is the Coastal Carolina Regional Manager for the NCDMVA and has recently celebrated her sixth anniversary with the organization. She passionately advocates for veterans by collaborating with various agencies and organizations. Jennifer conducts outreach programs for veterans, trains VSOs, assists in filing claims for veterans and their dependents, and educates them about their benefits. She is well-known for her unwavering support for veterans in any setting, and we are proud to honor her many contributions!

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we honor individuals from across our district whose lives reflect the very best of who we are. This week, we shine a light on a man whose journey is a testament to faith in action and leadership through service. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Donald Schuler Jr. of Lower Makefield.
 
Raised by two pastors‚ÄîDonald and Dawn‚Äîfaith and service were a constant part of his upbringing. From a young age, Don was taught true purpose is found in helping others and living with intention. That foundation would guide every step of his journey.
 
Don‚Äôs path of purpose began at Pennsbury High School, where he was known as a thoughtful leader and someone who was looked up to by others. He served as a Student Council senator, played football, volunteered as a Pop Warner coach, and gave countless hours to his community, volunteering and striving to make a difference wherever he could. In 2006, he was named YMCA Youth Volunteer of the Year and received a Senatorial Citation for his service‚Äîearly signs of a young man committed to leading by example.
 
Don's journey took him from the hallways of Pennsbury to the national stage. A dynamic leader and creative voice, his career has spanned industries and inspired audiences nationwide. As an Executive Success Coach, motivational speaker, and innovative storyteller, Don has partnered with major brands such as Google, Verizon, Budweiser, Campbell‚Äôs, and the NBA‚Äîbringing his message of purpose and empowerment to corporate, educational, and community spaces alike. He has delivered TEDx talks, led national speaking tours, and motivated thousands of students to believe in themselves and their potential.
 
Through it all, one thing remained clear: Don‚Äôs heart never left the community that raised him.
 
Today, Don has come home to serve as the Youth Ministries Pastor at The Crossing Church in Washington Crossing. In his newest role, through mentorship, ministry, and everyday presence, Don is helping our students discover who they are, grow in their faith, and realize the power of living with intention. He's not just encouraging them to find their purpose‚Äîhe‚Äôs walking alongside them as they do.
 
In a world where our young people are bombarded with a multitude of distractions, Don is a steady, guiding voice‚Äîhelping them build confidence, character, and a foundation of faith that will carry them into lives of meaning and service.
 
Don's return is more than a homecoming‚Äîit is a fulfillment of a calling. His life is a powerful reminder that our greatest purpose is found in what we give back, and for Don, that purpose is clear: to lead, to serve, and to help young people discover their purpose, grow in their faith, and give back to the communities that raised them.
 
Please join me in celebrating this remarkable man for his outstanding service, his unwavering dedication to our next generation, and the inspiring example he sets for us all‚Äîthank you, Don, for all you do!

Foxx goes on to argue that a discharge petition is a ‚Äúlast ditch demarche‚Äù that ‚Äúsidesteps the authority vested in the House‚Äôs committees.‚Äù

I‚Äôll let you all in on some insider baseball: even if legislation passes through a committee, Leadership can just let the bill die there. Name: Luna, Anna Paulina
text:
Here, Foxx intentionally mischaracterizes what my resolution does and its constitutionality.

The resolution gives pregnant Members with DIRE health concerns, as well as new mothers and fathers in Congress, the ability to vote by proxy. It does not give blanket permission to a pregnant Member or their spouse.

Name: Keating, William R.

I contacted the Department of Homeland Security to make clear that the Trump Administration should not be detaining and deporting legal residents like Rumeysa Ozturk just because they hold an opposing political view. Unless the administration can provide compelling evidence that justifies her ongoing detention and revocation of status, they must release Rumeysa Ozturk and restore her visa.

I requested explanations from Secretary Noem about why Ozturk was arrested, why and how her visa was revoked, what policies are in place to revoke visas overall, and what polices have been put in place specifically for students. As a former District Attorney, I am deeply interested in an explanation, too, on why she was arrested in the manner she was by masked, plain clothed officers, why she was transported so quickly to Louisiana, and how quickly she was given access to an attorney.
As I said yesterday, the majority must step up next week when we return to DC so we can exercise our Congressional oversight role and end these un-American attacks on legal residents.

text:
Our educators are on the front lines of shaping the next generation‚Äîand today, I had the honor of hearing directly from them.

I sat down with Jennifer Statler of the @PSEA and an incredible group of constituents educators from Pennsbury, Council Rock, Central Bucks, and school districts across our region. They shared powerful, firsthand insight into the challenges they face every day‚Äîunderfunded classrooms, teacher shortages, the growing mental health crisis among students, early literacy gaps, and the importance of reliable school meals.

These aren‚Äôt abstract policy issues‚Äîthey‚Äôre real, urgent, and deeply personal. And they‚Äôre exactly the kind of challenges I‚Äôm working to address in Congress.

Our district is home to some of the best educators and schools in the country, and I‚Äôll keep doing everything I can to support them‚Äîwith the resources, respect, and results they deserve.

Name: Peters, Gary C.
text:
The President‚Äôs executive order stripping federal workers of their collective bargaining rights at agencies like the Departments of Defense, Homeland Security, Veterans Affairs, and Health and Human Services is a betrayal of the hardworking people who dedicate their lives to serving our nation, including one-third who are veterans. This action will make our nation less safe and undercut the critical operations that Americans count on ‚Äì such as protecting national security, providing care to veterans and responding to emergencies ‚Äì by eliminating federal workers‚Äô ability to organize for better workplace conditions.

This executive order not only removes a key avenue for federal workers to resolve issues without disrupting government operations, it will also continue to undermine morale and make it harder to recruit and retain the nonpartisan experts needed to effectively protect and serve the American people.

I grew up in a union household, and I know firsthand how unions benefit hardworking families. I call on the President to reverse this order so that our dedicated public servants can continue to effectively provide the services that Americans count on every day.

My joint statement with Leader @SteveScalise, @GOPMajorityWhip, and @RepLisaMcClain on the SAVE Act, which the House will vote on later this week:
¬†
American citizens ‚Äî and only American citizens ‚Äî should decide American elections. House Republicans are determined to codify this commonsense idea with the SAVE Act which puts in place commonsense safeguards to prevent noncitizens from abusing our democratic process. This legislation cements into law President Trump‚Äôs executive action to secure our voter registration process and protect the voices of American voters. We urge all our colleagues in the House to join us in doing what the overwhelming majority of people in this country rightfully demand and deserve.

As National Nutrition Month comes to a close, I‚Äôm introducing the Nutrition Counseling Aiding Recovery for Eating Disorders (Nutrition CARE) Act with @RepBrianFitz, @RepPaulTonko & @RepDonBacon. 

This bill will expand access to life-saving eating disorder treatment for seniors.

Eating disorders affect seniors at rates similar to the general population, but Medicare doesn‚Äôt cover Medical Nutrition Therapy (MNT) for these conditions, leaving seniors & people with disabilities without access to necessary treatment.

Left untreated, eating disorders can lead to heart failure, kidney failure, diabetes, and more, which is why the Nutrition CARE Act is so critical. This bill will help ensure that all individuals with eating disorders can access the services they need to recover and stay healthy.

I'm grateful to my colleagues for partnering with me to make Medicare more comprehensive. For more information on the bill and @EDCoalition and my colleagues' statements in support, please visit:

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1748, the ancient ruins of Pompeii were rediscovered by Spanish engineer Rocque Joaqu√≠n de Alcubierre nearly 1,700 years after its destruction.

Pompeii was an ancient Roman city near modern Naples, Italy, that was buried under volcanic ash and pumice when Mount Vesuvius erupted in 79 AD. Because of this, the city was well-preserved, freezing daily life in time.  

Initial excavations after its rediscovery revealed buildings, frescoes, mosaics, and even casts of the city's residents, who had been caught in the eruption.

More than 42 million Americans rely on SNAP‚Äînearly 70% are children, seniors, or individuals with disabilities.

Yet under current law, they can‚Äôt use those benefits to buy hot meals like soup or rotisserie chicken. That doesn‚Äôt make sense‚Äîand limits access to nutritious food.
 
As part of my ongoing efforts to improve food access and nutrition for working families, seniors, and vulnerable individuals in our community, I introduced the Hot Foods Act‚Äîbipartisan, bicameral legislation that would allow SNAP recipients to purchase hot, prepared meals.
 
Whether it‚Äôs a parent picking up dinner after a long shift or a senior without access to a kitchen‚Äîthis bill gives people the flexibility to choose meals that are practical, healthy, and ready to eat.
 
This is a commonsense step toward better nutrition and food security for families in our community and across the nation.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
This morning, I had the honor of speaking at a Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute briefing on Capitol Hill, where I highlighted the urgent challenges facing Colonias. These communities are close to my heart, and I am dedicated to addressing their pressing housing and infrastructure needs. 

I have worked on these needs since my earliest days in the Texas state government. I wrote and passed the landmark bill on colonias in 1995, which enabled us to regulate and improve the lives of residents. 

Now, in Congress, I have secured tens of millions of dollars for colonias‚Äô water infrastructure, workforce support, and more. I am continuing to work to establish an office specifically for colonias in the US Department of Agriculture. 

Every American deserves a safe, dignified place where they can live and work. Together we can make that happen. 

I am grateful to the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute for giving me the platform to discuss such an important issue. I remain fully committed to advancing housing, infrastructure, and economic development in these communities. My office is always here to support and serve.

I was proud to join Congresswoman Luna as the 218th signature on her discharge petition to bring a vote to the House floor to allow expectant mothers and new parents to vote by proxy. The discharge petition process is well established, Rep. Luna followed the rules, and she deserves an up or down vote. Voting to block her discharge petition and change House rules in the middle of the 119th Congress would have set a dangerous precedent and limited the rights of each member.
